SIMPLE: tract
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tract
<hw>Tract</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev.fr.
<ets>tractate</ets>.]</ety> <def>A written discourse or dissertation,
generally of short extent; a short treatise, especially on practical
religion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The church clergy at that time writ the best collection of
<qex>tracts</qex> against popery that ever appeared.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tracts for the Times</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Tractarian</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tract</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tract
<hw>Tract</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tractus</ets> a drawing,
train, track, course, tract of land, from <ets>trahere tractum</ets>, to
draw. Senses 4 and 5 are perhaps due to confusion with <ets>track</ets>.
See <er>Trace</er>,<pos>v.</pos>, and cf. <er>Tratt</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Something drawn out or extended; expanse.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The deep <xex>tract</xex> of hell.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A region or quantity of land or water, of indefinite
extent; an area; <as>as, an unexplored <ex>tract</ex> of
sea</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A very high mountain joined to the mainland by a narrow
<qex>tract</qex> of earth.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Traits; features; lineaments.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The discovery of a man's self by the <qex>tracts</qex> of his
countenance is a great weakness.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The footprint of a wild beast.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Track; trace.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Efface all <qex>tract</qex> of its traduction.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But flies an eagle flight, bold, and forthon,⟦br⟧
Leaving no <qex>tract</qex> behind.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Treatment; exposition.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Continuity or extension of anything; <as>as, the
<ex>tract</ex> of speech</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Older.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Continued or protracted duration; length;
extent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Improved by <xex>tract</xex> of time.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>Verses of Scripture sung at
Mass, instead of the Alleluia, from Septuagesima Sunday till the
Saturday befor Easter; -- so called because sung <xex>tractim</xex>, or
without a break, by one voice, instead of by many as in the
antiphons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Region; district; quarter; essay; treatise;
dissertation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tract</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tract
<hw>Tract</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To trace out; to track; also, to
draw out; to protact.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au>
<au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tractability</ent>⟦br⟧
